SENATE RESOLUTION 297
By Yager
A RESOLUTION to honor the memory of Sister Carrie Elizabeth
Rowan Barksdale of Harriman.
WHEREAS, we were greatly saddened to learn of the passing of Sister Carrie Elizabeth
Rowan Barksdale of Harriman; and
WHEREAS, Carrie Barksdale was an exemplary public servant and consummate
professional who worked assiduously to improve the quality of life for her fellow citizens in
numerous capacities; and
WHEREAS, born on June 16, 1927, Mrs. Barksdale was the daughter of Blanche Rowan
and Charlie Murdock and attended Campbell High School in Rockwood; and
WHEREAS, throughout her professional career, Mrs. Barksdale demonstrated
dedication and perseverance through her work at the Federal Bakery Shop, the Tennessee
School of Beauty, and the Oak Ridge Racquet, as well as in private homes in Oak Ridge; and
WHEREAS, a woman of many talents and interests, Mrs. Barksdale was blessed to
travel throughout the country and across the world, enriching her life with both meaningful
experiences and cultural discovery; in particular, her journey to Jerusalem deeply touched her
heart and spirit, marking it as one of the most emotional and sacred moments of her life; and
WHEREAS, Carrie Barksdale was wholly devoted to her faith and an active member of
Sevier Drive Church of Christ, where she served in several capacities throughout the years; her
vision and obedience to God led her to establish Ladies Inspiration Day fifty-one years ago, an
enduring ministry that has uplifted women and churches in Tennessee and Georgia; and
WHEREAS, no stranger to awards and accolades, Carrie Barksdale received the Key to
the City of Harriman in 1998 from Mayor Harold Wester and again from current Mayor Wayne
Best; she was honored by the Highway 27 Church of Christ in Summerville, Georgia, for her
SR0297
013150
- 1 -

contributions to Ladies Inspiration Day, and she was the recipient of the Pioneer Christian
Award and the Hard Fighting Soldier Award; and
WHEREAS, in addition to being named a Golden Treasure by Roane County, Mrs.
Barksdale was honored at the fortieth annual Ladies Inspiration Day at the Sevier Drive Church
of Christ in 2015 for her loyalty and selfless service; she received tributes from Governor Bill
Haslam, Harriman City Mayor Chris Mason, and Senator Ken Yager for her influence and
lifelong commitment to her faith and her community; and
WHEREAS, Carrie Barksdale was a leader in her community and served the Tennessee
State Youth Conference as a counselor, the Knoxville Track Club as a treasurer, the Roane
County Choral Society as a soprano singer, and the former Harriman Hospital as a volunteer
and Pink Lady; she was also a representative for the March of Dimes and served as a board
member of Keep Roane Beautiful; and
WHEREAS, Carrie Barksdale was deeply devoted to her family, and she always
endeavored to remain true to family values of the highest order; and
WHEREAS, she will be sadly missed but fondly remembered by her daughters, Darlene
(Charles) Johnson, Marcia McMahan, Trellis Barksdale, and Sharrieffa Barksdale; her special
cousins, Alice Pettus and Ennis Sumrell; and a host of nieces, nephews, grandchildren, great-
grandchildren, great-great-grandchildren, cousins, and friends; and
WHEREAS, in addition to her parents, Mrs. Barksdale was preceded in death by her
husband, Marcellus Barksdale; her half-brother, Charles William Kimbrough; her half-sister, Dee
Stafford; her daughters, Eleece Barksdale McCleskey and Phadra Barksdale Hanks; her son,
Val Barksdale; her sons-in-law, Gary McMahan and Tommy McCleskey; and her grandson,
Albert Marcellus Hanks; and
- 2 - 013150

WHEREAS, Mrs. Barksdale lived her life with purpose, faith, humility, and joy, and she
greatly impacted the lives of those who were blessed to know her; her life was a testimony of
perseverance, kindness, and unwavering devotion to God, her family, and her community; and
WHEREAS, she leaves behind an indelible legacy of integrity and probity in public life,
compassion and loyalty in private life, and diligence and dedication in all her chosen endeavors;
and
WHEREAS, it is fitting that the members of this legislative body should pause to
remember the bountiful life of this exceptional public servant and human being; now, therefore,
BE IT RESOLVED BY THE SENATE OF THE ONE HUNDRED FOURTEENTH
GENERAL ASSEMBLY OF THE STATE OF TENNESSEE, that we hereby honor the memory of
Sister Carrie Elizabeth Rowan Barksdale, reflecting fondly upon her impeccable character and
her stalwart commitment to living the examined life with courage and conviction.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that we express our sympathy and offer our condolences
to the family and friends of Mrs. Barksdale.
BE IT FURTHER RESOLVED, that an appropriate copy of this resolution be prepared
for presentation with this final clause omitted from such copy.
